tself, or within the structure of a specific genre of literature. Salter attempts to negotiate a path through a set of methodological and interpretive issues in order to arrive at a better understanding of how people may have read and what they may have read. This, in turn, leads on to how we may interpret the evidence that manuscripts and early printed books provide for the ways that medieval and early modern people engaged with reading.This book will be of interest to academics and research students who study the history of reading, popular culture, literacy, manuscript and print culture, as well as to those interested more generally in medieval and early modern society and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBooks and readingxHistoryx16th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aBooks and readingxHistoryxTo 1500xGreat Britain. 0aBooks and readingzGreat BritainxHistoryy16th century. 0aBooks and readingzGreat BritainxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismxEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismxMiddle English, 1100-1500. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aEnglish.  aearly modern England.  afictional literature.  aliterary form.  aliterary voice.  amanuscript.  amaterial evidence.  amoral reading.  apage layout.  apopular reading.  apractical texts.  aprinted book.  areading experience.  areading practice.  areligious texts.1 aSalter, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://www.degruy